 bridges regional studies of South Asia and Britain while straddling the fields of racial theory, masculinity, imperialism, identity politics, and military studies. Of particular importance is the way it exposes the historical instability of racial categories based on colour and its insistence that historically specific ideologies of masculinity helped form the logic of imperial defence, thus wedding gender theory with military studies in unique ways. Moreover, Martial Races challenges the marginalisation of the British Army in histories of Victorian popular culture, and demonstrates the army’s enduring impact on the regional cultures of the Highlands, the Punjab and Nepal.This unique study will make fascinating reading for higher level students and experts in imperial history, military history and gender history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGorkha (South Asian people)xHistoryy19th century. 0aGorkha (South Asian people)zGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aMasculinity. 0aScotszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aSikhszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritish Empire.  aBritish popular culture.  aHighlands.  aIndia.  aNepalese Gurkhas.  aPunjabi Sikhs.  aRebellion of 1857.  aScottish Highlanders.  aVictorian culture.  aarts of war.  agendered language.  aidentity politics.  aimperialism.  amartial races.  amasculinity.  amilitary studies.  anineteenth-century ideology.  aracial theory.1 aStreets, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779394240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978184